==Usage== <!--T:9-->

<!--T:17-->
# Select a single object.
# There are several ways to invoke the command:
#* If the [[Part_Workbench|Part Workbench]] is active: press the {{Button|[[Image:Part_ColorPerFace.svg|16px]] [[Part_ColorPerFace|Appearance per Face]]}} button.
#* Select the {{MenuCommand|View → [[Image:Part_ColorPerFace.svg|16px]] Appearance per Face}} option from the menu.
#* Select the {{MenuCommand|[[Image:Part_ColorPerFace.svg|16px]] Appearance per Face}} option from the [[Tree_View|Tree View]] context menu.
# The '''Appearance per Face''' task panel opens.
# Select one or more faces:
#* Hold down {{KEY|Ctrl}} to select mutliple faces.
#* Optionally press the {{Button|Box Selection}} button, click in an empty area and drag a rectangle to select all faces belonging to the object that are (partially) inside the rectangle. Multiple box selections can be specified.
# Do one of the following:
#* Select a material from the list.
#*# Optionally press the {{Button|Launch Editor}} button to launch the [[Material_Edit|Material Editor]].
#* Specify a '''Custom appearance''':
#*# Press the {{Button|Appearance}} button.
#*# The '''Material Properties''' dialog box opens:<br>[[Image:Material_Properties_Dialog.png]]
#*# These properties can be edited:
#*#* '''Ambient color''': color of a surface under indirect, uniform lighting. Determines the color of the shadows on a surface.
#*#* '''Diffuse color''': base color when illuminated by light.
#*#* '''Emissive color''': color of a surface that appears to emit as if it were a light source, independent of external lighting, making the object look self-illuminated. Set to black to have no emissive color.
#*#* '''Specular color''': color and intensity of the bright, mirror-like highlights that appear on shiny or reflective surfaces when light hits them directly. Set to bright colors for shiny objects.
#*#* '''Shininess''': the size and sharpness of specular highlights on a surface. Higher values produce small, sharp highlights, while lower values create broad, soft highlights. Note that the highlight intensity is defined by specular color.
#*#* '''Transparency''': defines how transparent the surface is.
#*# Optionally press the {{Button|Reset}} button to change the appearance to that defined by the material.
#*# Optionally press the {{Button|Default}} button to change the appearance to match the current [[PartDesign_Preferences#Shape_appearance|preferences]].
#*# Press the {{Button|Close}} button when done.
#* Press the {{Button|Set to Default}} button to change the appearance to that defined by the material.
# Optionally select one or more new faces whose properties you want to change.
# Press the {{Button|OK}} button to close the task panel and finish the command.


